BOOK III

The voyages and settlements of Aeneas before his arrival at Carthage.

Tite time embraced in the narrative of this book is nearly seven years. It begins with the events immediately succeeding the fall of Troy, which oc· curred traditionally in 1184 tac. The Trojan fugitives, under the command of Aeneas, spent the remainder of the summer, and the following winter, in building ships in the harhor of Antandros (snb Antandro), a city on the southern side of hlount Ida. This was the first year, i.e. the first summer and winter, after the fall of Troy. The second year begins with the depar- ture of the exiles (early in the summer) for Thrace, and is spent in the attempt to establish aeolony there (ll. 13-69). In the third year the new colony, called Aenos or, as some think, Aenea, is abandoned, and the wan- derers, stopping at Delos to consult the oracl (l. 73), proceed to Crete (l. 131), and commence the colony of Pergameum (ll. 132-134). Haviug passed the fourth year and part of the fifth in Crete, they are compelled bya pestilence to give up this settlement also (l. 190), and sail to Actium in Acarnania, where they rernain during the 'fifth winter (l. 284). They resume their voyage in the beginning of the sixth summer, and first landing near Buthrotum, and meeting with llelenus and Andromache (ll. 294-505), they cross the Adriatic to Portus Veneris, in Apulia (l. 523), and from thence con· tinue their voyage along the coasts of Italy and Sicily to Drepanum (l. 707), which they reach at the close of the sixth snmrner, and where soon atter- wards Anchises dies (l. 710). In the beginning of the following, or seventh summer (see l, 34sqq.), they start for Italy, but are immediately driven bl ³ sternito the coast of Africa.
